ue for or against the death penalty. Instead, Dead Certainty contributes to a larger project in contemporary political and legal philosophy: re-imagining how people in today's world give coherence and meaning to their shared experience. Culbert's work will be of interest to scholars of political theory, jurisprudence, law and society, rhetoric, continental philosophy, and ethics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCapital punishmentxMoral and ethical aspectszUnited States. 0aCapital punishmentzUnited States. 0aJudgments, CriminalzUnited States. 7aLAW / Ethics & Professional Responsibility.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107042040 cprintz978080475745440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362682940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503626829423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503626829/original  a978-3-11-070420-4  Stanford University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles